## Chapter 1: The Sorting Ceremony
The atmosphere inside the Apex Dome was thick with the scent of ozone and collective panic. Three thousand seniors sat in the tiered stadium seats, their eyes locked onto the massive white platform in the center of the arena.
The Resonance Dais.
Above it, a massive holographic ticker projected live feeds of the results. Every time a student stepped up, the stadium speakers resonated with a low, metallic hum that vibrated straight through Kaelen’s ribcage.
"**Class: Aegis Vanguard. Tier: B. Scouting Offer: Ironclad Academy.**"
The crowd roared. Down on the floor, a towering kid from the track team raised his fists in triumph, bathed in the lingering gold light of his manifestation. Across the arena, recruiters from the city's top-tier institutions were already tapping furiously on their tablets, updating their draft lists.
Kaelen Vance adjusted the faded collar of his standard-issue high school uniform and let out a quiet breath. He wasn't tracking the recruiters. He was looking at his own palms. They were slightly damp.
For four years, Kaelen had survived by being perfectly, aggressively unnoticeable. His grades in Tactical Theory hovered at a solid 70%. In physical conditioning, he landed exactly in the middle of the pack. In a city built on hyper-competition, blending into the background was a survival mechanism. But today, the System stripped away every mask. Today, your soul was laid bare, measured, and branded with a letter grade.
"Next candidate," the automated voice boomed, completely devoid of empathy. "Sector 4, Seat 112. Kaelen Vance."
The two students sitting next to him shuffled their legs back, giving him room to pass. Nobody wished him luck. In the grand scheme of the Awakening Exam, an average student usually meant an average result—a Tier-D *Sentry* or a Tier-C *Logistics Coordinator* if he got lucky.
Kaelen walked down the concrete steps, his boots echoing against the metal grating of the arena floor. The air grew colder the closer he got to the dais.
Standing at the edge of the white stone platform was the Presiding Officer, a stern woman wearing the polished obsidian armor of the City Vanguard. She didn’t look at him. She just gestured toward the center of the ring.
"Step into the focal point. Place both hands on the core stone. Do not fight the resonance," she recited mechanically.
Kaelen stepped up. In the center of the dais sat a rough-cut block of glowing, iridescent crystal—the Core Stone, connected directly to the city’s localized System Node.
He took a slow breath, letting the freezing air steady his nerves, and pressed his palms flat against the cold surface of the stone.
Instantly, a shockwave of raw energy surged up his arms.
It didn't feel like the warm, empowering glow the high-tier students had described. It felt violent. Like a microscopic drill tracing the paths of his nervous system, tearing open locked doors inside his consciousness. The stadium around him faded into a blur of white noise as a sharp, piercing chime rang directly inside his skull.
**[Manifestation Complete.]**
**[Analyzing Soul Resonance...]**
**[Class Identified: Salvager]**
**[Innate Core Skill Evolved: Deconstruct (Level 1)]**
**[Threat Potential Evaluation: Tier-E (Commoner Class)]**
Kaelen blinked against the sudden glare as the light of the stone died down. There was no gold aura. No brilliant silver flash. Just a dim, sickly gray vapor that pooled around his boots for a second before evaporating into the chilly air.
Above him, the holographic ticker updated instantly.
"**Class: Salvager. Tier: E. Institutional Assignment: Anvil Ridge Vocational.**"
A heavy, suffocating silence fell over his section of the stadium. Then came the whispers. They weren’t loud, but in the vast space of the dome, they carried perfectly.
*"A Salvager? Are you serious? I didn't even know that was still on the exam roster."*
*"Basically a glorified garbage man."*
*"Look at the assignment. Anvil Ridge. That graveyard on the edge of the industrial sector? He might as well just go work the assembly lines now."*
Up in the recruiters' booth, not a single head turned. The scouts didn't even bother to log the result. A Tier-E auxiliary class had zero combat value to the guilds, and zero prestige for the corporate sponsorships.
The Presiding Officer finally looked down at him, her expression a mix of professional detachment and faint pity.
"Step down, Candidate Vance. Take the exit corridor to the left to collect your orientation packet. Next candidate!"
Kaelen pulled his hands away from the stone. His palms were stained with a faint, metallic gray residue that quickly absorbed into his skin. His limbs felt incredibly heavy, a physical reaction to the System locking his growth potential to the lowest possible threshold.
He didn't look back at the stadium seats. He didn't look at his classmates. He walked toward the dim, narrow corridor labeled *Auxiliary Exits*.
As he stepped into the shadows of the hallway, away from the flashing lights of the arena, he pulled up his personal status screen with a thought.
**[Kaelen Vance]**
 * **Class:** Salvager (Tier-E)
 * **Level:** 1
 * **Strength:** 8 | **Agility:** 9 | **Vitality:** 8 | **Aetheric Resonance:** 2
 * **Active Skills:**
   * **[Deconstruct (Lv.1)]** - *Allows the user to break down broken equipment, standard scrap, or low-level physical structures into basic raw materials. (Efficiency: 40%).*
It was a dead end. In this world, your stats only increased when you leveled up your class, and an auxiliary class like *Salvager* only gained experience by dismantling trash.
Kaelen stopped in the empty corridor, leaning his back against the cold concrete wall. He stared at the description of **[Deconstruct]**.
He closed his eyes, remembering the whispers, the recruiters looking away, the bleak future of a name-only academy meant for the dregs of society.
"A garbage man," Kaelen muttered to himself, his fingers curling into tight fists against the wall.
Suddenly, a strange sensation flared in the center of his chest. It wasn't the freezing bite of the Core Stone. It was a hot, localized throb, right where the metallic residue had sunk into his skin.
A tiny, secondary text window, completely separate from the standard System interface, flickered at the very bottom of his vision in a dark, blood-red font.
**[System Restriction Error Detected...]**
**[Core Skill 'Deconstruct' possesses unmapped architectural parameters.]**
**[Target criteria expanded: Material components, Organic matter, Crystallized Essence.]**
**[Warning: Bypassing safety limits may cause structural strain to the host.]**
Kaelen’s breath hitched. He stared at the red text until it slowly faded away, leaving his standard, pathetic gray status screen behind.
He looked down at his right hand. The skin looked exactly the same, but beneath it, he could feel a faint, foreign hum—like a hidden engine waiting for fuel.
He wasn't going to the factories. And he wasn't going to spend his life sweeping up after the elites. If the world was only going to give him scrap, he would just have to tear the world apart to see what it was made of.
